@kohl1999 Its so much larger than the modern gaming audience so they should be very happy. 
These products was not designed to sell in the first place as I see it. 
And no Disney can not fix it without firing most of the management.

@Tiah-mm8lp Iron-Heart isn't new though. It was made a couple years ago, they've just been sitting on it as well as doing reshoots to attempt to make it more current. It isn't really a valid example of Marvel course correcting as Disney won't just not release a completed project (like WB did with the Batgirl movie). This is where you look at Thunderbolts, F4, and movies/films that are in current production.

Once Marvel kills their current universe and restarts with new casting in a couple years, I think they'll put out quality over quantity. They just need to finish their current projects and they'll have a clean slate after Secret Wars.

All Star Wars needs is a solid movie to kick off a new trilogy in order to course correct. It would have to be unique enough from what has been released though. If they made it in the time of The Old Republic or even 500 years after Luke, it would make it fresh enough. It just has to be NEW. Not a reboot, or a familiar story retold (like the last trilogy was).

@Obiejerusalem We need to start a movement to introduce youngsters to the gems of the past. Films like, Goodbye Mr. Chips (1939), Ninotchka (1939), Stagecoach (1939), Dark Victory (1939), Of Mice in Men (1939), Mr. Smith Goes to Washington (1939).

The reality is, this stuff in the present is not improving, and they don't care to improve. They don't see anything wrong, they wish to continue. We need to make our peace with it, and move on. On average, how many youngsters have seen a film like High Noon or the Man Who Shot Liberty Valance? Not a lot. We have to pass down (and be stewards of) the Golden Age of Hollywood to the next generation.
I think schools should have a certain set of films they have to have every kid watch and write a report on it.

